MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
OF
EL PASO ELECTRIC COMPANY
PROVIDING FOR
SALES OF CAPACITY, ENERGY AND/OR ANCILLARY SERVICES
EL PASO ELECTRIC COMPANY MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
TABLE OF CONTENTS
1 Definitions 1.1 Commission 1.2 Customer 1.3 EPE 1.4 Four Corners Market 1.5 Palo Verde Market 1.6 SPS Market 1.7 Tariff 1.8 Transaction 1.9 Transaction Confirmation 1.10 Energy Imbalance Market 2 Availability 3 Character of Service 4 Rates 5 Transaction Confirmation 6 Expansion of Facilities 7 Revisions to Tariff 8 Effective Date 9 Compliance with Commission Regulations 10 Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority 11 Seller Category
1 DEFINITIONS The following terms with initial letters capitalized shall have the specified meanings when used in this Market-Based Rate Tariff ("Tariff"): 1.1 "Commission"
"Commission" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.2 "Customer"
"Customer" means an entity that enters into a Transaction under this Tariff. 1.3 "EPE"
"EPE" means El Paso Electric Company. 1.4 "Four Corners Market"
"Four Corners Market" means the markets directly interconnected with the generating stations at Four Corners in Northwestern New Mexico. 1.5 "Palo Verde Market"
"Palo Verde Market" means the markets directly interconnected with the Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Station located west of Phoenix, Arizona. 1.6 " SPS Market "
"SPS Market" means sales by EPE through its system's interconnection with Southwestern Public Service Company. 1.7 "Tariff"
"Tariff" means this Market-Based Rate Tariff as it may be amended and/or superseded from time to time. 1.8 "Transaction"
"Transaction" means an individual transaction scheduled pursuant to this Tariff. 1.9 "Transaction Confirmation"
"Transaction Confirmation" means the agreement and any supplements thereto entered into by a Customer and EPE for service under this Tariff. A Transaction Confirmation may be oral or written. 1.10 "California Independent System Operator's Energy Imbalance Market" (CAISO EIM) "CAISO EIM" means the real-time wholesale energy market to manage transmission congestion and optimize procurement of imbalance energy (positive or negative) to balance supply and demand deviations, which is managed by the CAISO.
2 AVAILABILITY
2.1 This Tariff is available for sales of capacity and/or electric energy by EPE in the Four Corners Market, the Palo Verde Market, the SPS Market and all markets directly or indirectly interconnected to those markets (including all balancing authority areas except EPE's own balancing authority area), where such sales are not otherwise subject to another tariff, rate schedule or agreement on file with the Commission. EPE has been authorized to transact at market-based rates in the CAISO EIM market (El Paso Electric Company, Order Accepting Notice of Change in Status, 182 FERC 61,192 (2023)). 2.2 No entity affiliated with EPE is eligible for service under this Tariff except pursuant to a separate filing with the Commission under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act. 2.3 Mitigated Sales: Sales of energy and capacity are permissible under this Tariff in all balancing authority areas where EPE has been granted market-based rate authority. Sales of energy and capacity under this Tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary between EPE's mitigated balancing authority area and a balancing authority area where EPE has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i) legal title of the power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing authority area where EPE has market-based rate authority; and (ii) if EPE sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated balancing authority area from the outside. EPE must retain, for a period of five years from the date of the sale, all data and information related to the sale that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above.
3 CHARACTER OF SERVICE
3.1 EPE may provide capacity and/or energy under this Tariff in varying amounts at varying levels of firmness or priorities of service, for varying periods of service, and in accordance with varying delivery schedules as agreed to between EPE and the Customer. If necessary, transmission and ancillary services needed to complete transactions will be established by agreement between EPE and the Customer. To the extent transmission is required over EPE's transmission system, EPE or the Customer will acquire such transmission under EPE's Open Access Transmission Tariff. 3.2 Ancillary Services: 3.2.1 California: EPE offers regulation service, spinning reserve service and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. 3.2.2 Third-party provider/Third-party ancillary services: EPE offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
4 RATES
The rates for purchases under this Tariff shall be as agreed to by EPE and the Customer. 5 TRANSACTION CONFIRMATION
5.1 Prior to the commencement of service to a Customer, EPE and the Customer will confirm the transaction ("Transaction Confirmation"). 5.2 EPE may refuse, at its sole discretion, to enter into a Transaction under this Tariff. 5.3 Acceptance of service by the Customer commits the Customer to the provisions of this Tariff and to the terms of the Transaction Confirmation. All other terms and conditions of any sale under this Tariff shall be established by agreement between Customer and EPE.
6 EXPANSION OF FACILITIES
EPE will have no obligation under this Tariff or any Transaction entered into hereunder to plan its system, to enlarge or modify its facilities, or operate its system in such a manner in order to provide or maintain capacity and/or energy sold under this Tariff. 7 REVISIONS TO TARIFF
EPE may file revisions to this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of EPE unilaterally to file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 or 206 of the Federal Power Act pursuant to the Commission's Rules and Regulations.
8 EFFECTIVE DATE
This Tariff shall be effective on the date established by the Commission.
9 COMPLIANCE WITH COMMISSION REGULATIONS
EPE shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning EPE's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes EPE to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits EPE's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning EPE's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 10 LIMITATIONS AND EXEMPTIONS REGARDING MARKET-BASED RATE AUTHORITY
Limitations: EPE does not have market-based rate authority for sales within its balancing authority area. See letter order issued March 29, 2017 in El Paso Electric Company, Docket No. ER10-2721-006 (). Exemptions: The Commission has granted EPE the following waivers: waiver of the provisions of Subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission's regulations regarding the filing of rate schedules, with the exception of sections 35.12 (a), 35.13 (b), 35.15 and 35.16. See El Paso Electric Company, 87 FERC 61,219 (1999).
11 SELLER CATEGORY EPE is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Southwest region, and a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in all other regions.
